<p>By BG John Sullivan, Chief of Transportation, SCOE; COL Mark Mueller, TRADOC Capabilities Manager, SCOE; LTC(R) Jeff Brown, SCOE;<br />December 19, 2014</p>
<p>The U.S. Army Operating Concept:  Win in a Complex World 2020-2040, "describes how future Army forces will prevent conflict, shape security environments, and win wars while operating as part of our Joint Force and working with multiple partners."<span class="endnoteRef">[1]</span>  In order to "win in a complex world," the Army Operating Concept (AOC) emphasizes that "Army forces must provide the Joint Force with multiple options, integrate the efforts of multiple partners, operate across multiple domains, and present our enemies and adversaries with multiple dilemmas."<span class="endnoteRef">[2]</span>  In this context, the current and future Army watercraft fleet supports the AOC idea of joint combined arms operations:  an expansion of the traditional concept of combined arms to include the integration of not only joint capabilities, but also the broad range of efforts necessary to accomplish the mission.<span class="endnoteRef">[3]</span></p>
<p>To conduct joint combined arms operations, Army combined arms teams integrate with other services and mission partners to conduct joint combined arms maneuver – the synchronized application of two or more arms or elements of one service, along with the application of joint, interorganizational, and multinational capabilities to place the adversary in positions of disadvantage.<span class="endnoteRef">[4]</span>  The most important idea to understanding the role of future Army forces in joint combined arms maneuver is that "Army operations are inherently cross-domain operations. U.S. forces depend on and complement joint efforts in the land, air, maritime, space, and cyberspace domains to enable operations on land."<span class="endnoteRef">[5]</span></p>
<p>As the Army takes on the challenges of developing the future force, it will need to closely examine all of its current capabilities in terms of their roles in the kind of interdependent, cross-domain joint force operations envisaged in the joint combined arms maneuver idea.  The purpose of this article is to examine one of those capabilities – the Army's watercraft fleet – and how it can and should fit into a future Army designed to conduct cross-domain joint combined arms maneuver in the complex world described in the AOC.</p>
<p class="BubbleTitleSection">Army Watercraft:  A Land Power Capability</p>
<p>Section 3062 of United States Code:  Title 10 - ARMED FORCES, states "In general, the Army, within the Department of the Army, includes land combat 	and service forces and such aviation and water transport as may be organic therein. It shall be organized, trained, and equipped primarily for prompt and 	sustained combat incident to operations on land."  Pursuant to Title 10, the Army maintains a small, but versatile watercraft fleet designed to support the Army's land-based mission.  Currently, the Army watercraft fleet includes landing craft capable of moving a variety of forces and cargo, and vessels and other systems, such as tugs, floating cranes, and mobile communications platforms, to support water terminal operations.<span class="endnoteRef">[6]</span>  Unlike naval forces that are designed, resourced and trained to conduct combat operations at sea, the Army's watercraft fleet is designed to provide tactical mobility in support of land-based combat operations.</p>
<p>The Army watercraft fleet provides land forces the capability to move personnel, equipment, and supplies, and conduct heavy sustainment operations through coastal waterways; austere, degraded, or unimproved ports or harbors; and over bare beach environments in support of joint logistics over-the-shore (JLOTS) operations.  The figure below depicts some of the vessels and systems currently in operation in the Army's Watercraft Fleet.</p>
