<p>The Army vision in the AOC is one that is capable of conducting joint combined arms maneuver across the land, air, maritime and cyberspace domains; an Army capable of integrating with and synchronizing joint, interorganizational, and multinational partners to present unexpected and multiple dilemmas to an enemy adapted to a complex operational environment.  In this context, Army watercraft provides a critical capability to conduct joint combined arms maneuver to, in, from and through the maritime domain and those areas of the land domain dominated by water.</p>
<p>Unlike naval forces that are designed, manned, equipped, and trained to conduct operations at sea, Army watercraft are designed, manned, equipped, and trained as part of the land force.  Employing Army watercraft in concert with its land, air and cyberspace capabilities provides Army forces with the tactical mobility, depth, simultaneity, and endurance to conduct operations across all domains.  Employed in concert with joint, interorganizational and multinational partners, Army watercraft provide the key and essential interfaces needed to synchronize joint combined arms operations to present multiple and unexpected dilemmas for the enemy.  Army watercraft, designed and employed in the context of the ideas presented in the AOC, will provide future Army forces with the ability to move beyond the two-dimensional air-land mindset to one that is based on true cross-domain operations.</p>
